(1201, 1, '2018-03-29 07:38:19', '2018-03-29 07:38:19', 'Is Bitcoin a bubble? We analyse the controversial cryptocurrency.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Is bitcoin a bubble?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>A while ago I was asked by a colleague in the industry to provide some brief views on Bitcoin and whether it was a bubble. The below was my response.</em>\r\n\r\nIn short, my view is that bitcoin has not reached a sufficient price to be classified as a bubble. Bubbles are typically defined as an unsustainable increase in the price of some asset well beyond any reasonable approximation of its underlying value. In order to consider whether bitcoin is a bubble or not, we would require some approximation of what its value is as well as some reasoning as to why the current price is unsustainable.\r\n\r\nBitcoin\'s primary function is as an anonymous unit of exchange, i.e. it can be used to perform some online transactions anonymously.  Yet it has problems in that it\'s rarely accepted by mainstream merchants (Expedia.com does for example but this is more the exceptional than the rule).\r\n\r\nIf we were to assume that Bitcoin eventually accrues the critical mass to be a useful unit of exchange (given its recent listing as a future contract on the CME, this may not be an unfair assumption) then we can more easily estimate its value. Global GDP according to the CIA world fact book was $U78.3 trillion in 2014 and it\'s estimated that trade via the black market is circa 20% of world GDP. If we were to assume a mere 10% of this market moves to bitcoin, the 21 million bitcoins (in <u>future</u> existence) would have a transaction value of circa $U1.56 trillion.\r\n\r\nGiven that each bitcoin in the above market estimate is utilised for a transaction several times, we must also adjust our estimates via the velocity of money. A study by ARK Investment Management and Coinbase suggested that circa half of the user base holds bitcoins as an investment (rather than as a unit of exchange). The money velocity of M1 in the US is currently about 5.5x so we adjust the transaction value by 11x (5.5x/.50) rendering a final valuation of circa $U6,780 per bitcoin.\r\n\r\nBased on bitcoin\'s latest price ($U6,900) it appears fair value...yet would 30% of the black market converting to bitcoin be unreasonable? Perhaps not. Whilst we have not taken into account any factor for the time value of monies invested, my view is that bitcoin does not appear to have reached a sufficient price as to satisfy the conditions for being a bubble.\r\n\r\nHowever those with a practical mind will immediately see the gaping hole in this argument - it assumes that bitcoin <strong>is</strong> the cryptocurrency of choice for the black market. Yet why should this be? As noted in an article by Reuters (<a href=\"https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cyber-attack-bitcoin/bitcoins-murkier-rivals-line-up-to-displace-it-as-cybercriminals-favourite-idUSKCN18E2F1\">link here</a>) <em>“If it was me, I would want people to use bitcoin all day, because you can trace it,” said Luke Wilson, vice president for law enforcement at Elliptic, a London-based security firm that tracks illicit bitcoin transactions and that counts the U.S. Federal Bureau for Investigations (FBI) among its clients.\" </em>Hence whilst we might believe that economically bitcoin can justify some upside, if the black market doesn\'t wish to use it due to it\'s trace-ability, it\'s almost surely worth much less than where it\'s currently trading.\r\n\r\nGiven the risks and hole in it\'s value proposition, we\'d be quite comfortable in passing on any opportunity to invest in bitcoin or its associated derivatives.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Is Bitcoin a bubble?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'is-bitcoin-a-bubble', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:33:02', '2018-08-23 11:33:02', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/2018/01/17/uber-is-selling-off-its-auto-leasing-business-copy/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1205, 1, '2018-03-29 07:41:14', '2018-03-29 07:41:14', 'How does the Vega fund minimise downside risk?\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: How the Vega fund minimises downside risk\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website  </em><em>constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega </em><em>Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on </em><em>this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would </em><em>encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\nThere\'s no escaping that if you sell a put option, you are taking on a small but very real risk that you could owe the buyer of said option a lot of money in the future. This is actually a necessity. To illustrate, let\'s consider the following example.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund recently wrote an option on the QQQ (NASDAQ mini index) for $600 per contract that has 113 days to expiry with a strike of 150. The QQQ at the time was trading at about 157 so we have somewhat of a buffer before the strike. We\'re required to put up about $2400 in margin so our return is 25% for 113 days. By inspection, we can see that before we begin to take a loss, the QQQ would need to fall from 157 to below 144 (9%) by July which is not impossible but is statistically unlikely. Since the probability of a loss is unlikely, the probability of profit by reflection is likely.\r\n\r\nI\'m sure you can see where I\'m going with this - for a likely as well as high return over such a short period, the writer of this contract must be willing to accept a large loss if the QQQ falls a lot. Otherwise, there\'s nothing in it for the buyer of the contract and the trade won\'t occur. As custodians of our clients capital, this presents downside risk which we must manage.\r\n\r\nWe first note that whilst the option will pay us a 25% return, Vega\'s proprietary model tells us that the \'fair\' return should only be 15% (a margin of safety of 10%). This means that option buyers are craving security so much that they\'re willing to pay over the fair price for it - a happy coincidence as we\'re willing to sell overpriced options. Hence the contract isn\'t really fair - we have a mathematical edge from the start. This doesn\'t mean that we can\'t take a loss on this particular trade (it\'s just that we have a bigger buffer for losses than we theoretically should have).\r\n\r\nVega\'s algorithm will only ever enter into mis-priced securities which adds to both downside protection and investor returns over time.\r\n\r\nWe can further reduce the potential for a large loss by only selling option premium in less risky economic times whilst moving to cash or buying protection during risky times. As many of those reading will know, The Vega Fund has a set of algorithms which determine how risky the economy and financial markets are. Currently the algorithms are telling us that the risk of a big loss is low (but such a view is subject to continuous monitoring so please, don\'t take this as a recommendation). In doing this, we further skew the odds and returns in favour of our investors.\r\n\r\nFinally, in conjunction to Vega\'s portfolio, we run a separate portfolio which hedges against sudden unforeseeable market drops - especially useful for this particular investment.\r\n\r\nTo summarise, due to lucrative option premiums and a strong economic environment Vega is currently writing options over many broad based market indices but is then also taking on risk which must be managed. Vega manages portfolio risk against the broader economic/financial environment, hedging excess risk and only entering into contracts with a good margin of safety.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund will be open to sophisticated investors <strong>by invitation</strong> from the 1st of July 2018.', 'How Vega minimises downside risk', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-vega-minimises-downside-risk', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:32:19', '2018-08-23 11:32:19', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/2018/01/17/bitcoin-is-the-gag-gift-copy/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2143, 1, '2018-04-08 13:04:27', '2018-04-08 13:04:27', 'How does Vega see the US economic cycle?\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: How does Vega see the US economic cycle?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nA core piece of the Vega investment strategy is to manage client’s capital with respect to the phase of the current economic/business cycle. Now if this were a simple process then everyone would be doing it but since it’s quite complicated, we’re going to outlay a little of our thinking on the matter.\r\n\r\nCycles typically have four parts, an expansion, a peak, a recession and a recovery. To start we can make some fairly obvious observations about the US economy.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>It doesn’t appear to be in recession.</li>\r\n 	<li>It has experienced a recovery post the contraction of 2009.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWhich leaves us to wonder whether the current economy is in an expansionary phase or has peaked. It would be difficult to determine the answer with 100 per cent certainty so we’ll speak in terms of probabilities.\r\n\r\nIf you’re a frequent reader of Howard Mark’s literature you’ll have read his January memo to clients (<a href=\"https://www.oaktreecapital.com/docs/default-source/memos/latest-thinking.pdf\">link</a>). Marks\' makes some pertinent economic observations:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><em>The U.S. economy is chugging along, and the recovery that started in 2009 has become one of the longest in history (103 months old at this point). The rest of the world’s economies are joining in for that rare thing, worldwide growth. Most economies seem to be gaining rather than losing steam, and they don’t appear likely to run out of it anytime soon.”</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Since the economic recovery hasn’t been marked by excesses to the upside, when a recession eventually does occur, it doesn’t have to be extreme. In short, no boom, no bust.</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>The unemployment rate is down to 4.1%, nearly the lowest level in 60 years, meaning we’re nearing “full employment” (albeit with an unusually low percentage of adults participating in the workforce). </em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>The low levels of inflation worldwide mean central bankers needn’t rush to raise interest rates to restrain it. There’s no obvious reason to predict hyperinflation. Thus the near-term rise in interest rates – while probable – can be expected to be gradual and limited in scope.</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSo in short the economy appears to be growing and economic indicators are positive. Given this as well as Vega’s algorithm based economic analysis, we would estimate that the likelihood that US is still expanding is perhaps 60/70% and the likelihood of a peak 30/40% - perhaps the latter more recently elevated by the possibility of a trade war between the US and China - but let’s not get carried away.\r\n\r\nThe latest economic data point for the US economy has been non-farm payrolls and the unemployment rate which came out Friday at 4.1% (consensus expectations was 4.0%). Since the economy is close to full employment, the natural process would be for wages from here to increase and lead to later inflation and some tempering via interest rates, but this is a gradual process as Marks noted.\r\n\r\nSo how is Vega’s option portfolio positioned for this environment given this view? Like Marks, we’re cautiously optimistic. The Vega portfolio is tilted towards expecting an inflation in stock market prices over the medium term. Economic risk however is increasing.\r\n\r\nOur hedging book is well placed to withstand any unforeseeable market volatility and we’re pleased with the margin of safety between market prices and the valuation of our portfolio. Given another quote from the memo, this seems prudent.\r\n\r\n<em>“Most valuation parameters are either the richest ever (Buffett ratio of stock market capitalization to GDP, price-to-sales ratio, the VIX, bond yields, private equity transaction multiples, real estate capitalisation ratios) or among the highest in history (p/e ratios, Shiller cycle-adjusted p/e ratio).”</em><!-- <fw_preview_session>1523192429084</fw_preview_session> -->', 'How does Vega see the US economic cycle?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-does-vega-see-the-us-economic-cycle', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:31:14', '2018-08-23 11:31:14', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/?p=2051', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2144, 1, '2018-04-17 00:00:35', '2018-04-17 00:00:35', 'Are we calling time for the US economy?\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Vega holds 50 per cent cash….are we bearish?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nFor anyone looking who’s looked at the Vega portfolio of late (a very select few individuals at this point in time), they would rightly observe that the Fund is only 50 per cent invested with the remaining 50 per cent being held in cash. So does this mean we’ve become suddenly bearish on the US economy?\r\n\r\nIn short <strong>no</strong>. To answer this question, we must understand how Vega views cash as an investment. Cash as observed by Warren Buffet is one of the poorest investments available – it by default provides no real capital growth over time and hence to hold significant quantities of cash is an inefficient use of capital.\r\n\r\nTypically, many investors will hold a portion of their portfolio in cash – waiting for an opportunistic entry into an investment or because there doesn’t appear to be ample investment opportunities in the market. Yet Vega is not finding investment opportunities to be scarce – quite the contrary, there are many.\r\n\r\nVega is holding 50 per cent of its portfolio in cash for several reasons.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>The investments in the portfolio have already very high payoffs, so even with substantial levels of cash, the portfolio has been constructed with a high probability of out-performance. Hence the portfolio does not need to take on more risk than it already is.</li>\r\n 	<li>Vega will always hold ample reserves of cash in order to handle any short term events where volatility is elevated. It’s notable that due to the high volatility of the options market, new opportunities arise at a higher frequency than that of the stock market.</li>\r\n 	<li>There is the potential for even better opportunities to arise which require higher levels of margin capital – the Vega Fund is hence well positioned to take advantage of these events.</li>\r\n 	<li>There is little need to go over-weight on risk when the market is fairly mature and economic/geopolitical risks are rising.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nHence we have a solid case for holding significant quantities of cash. We may hold more or less in the future, but that depends on what opportunities are out there and economic risk levels.\r\n\r\nTo summarise, the implied return of Vega’s cash reserves is more than just interest earned, it\'s allows us to easily position into better opportunities and hold the portfolio through volatile periods. In addition, the Vega portfolio has ample exposure and embedded alpha sufficient to generate market beating levels of performance for our clients.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund will be open to sophisticated investors <strong>by invitation</strong> from the 1st of July 2018.\r\n\r\n<!-- <fw_preview_session>1523848878574</fw_preview_session> -->', 'Vega holds 50 per cent cash….are we bearish?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'vega-has-60-per-cent-cash-are-we-bearish', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:30:31', '2018-08-23 11:30:31', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/?p=2066', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2145, 1, '2018-04-25 11:00:05', '2018-04-25 11:00:05', 'Redeploying capital from the QQQ to SPY\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: SPYing an opportunity\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nReaders will recall that the Vega Fund recently (see <a href=\"http://vegacapital.net/2018/03/29/how-vega-minimises-downside-risk/\">here</a>) held a short position in some July 150 strike put options on the NASDAQ mini index (QQQ). At the time these options had an inflated premium of $6 (Vega entered at $6.30) as technology stocks came under pressure amid the Facebook inquiry, the crash of an autonomous car and concerns that governments would regulate companies such as Facebook and Google more stringently.\r\n\r\nOur philosophy at the Vega Fund is that these events are largely noise. Looking longer term, most firms (not all) which dominate market indices have strong competitive positions and a long run of profitability ahead of them whether regulated or not….One must remember that the Tobacco industry enjoyed many a profitable year post heavy regulation – a counter-intuitive fact!\r\n\r\nHowever a July 2018 put is not a long term bet - it’s clearly short term. The underlying stock index should behave largely randomly within this time-frame hence we employed statistics combined with Vega’s macroeconomic analysis to assess the opportunity and risk. The outcome of this was that the option which was yielding a 25 per cent return to July if priced fairly should have offered only 15 per cent or less (embedded alpha of 10 per cent). In addition, whilst a financial market shock was possible, it was also statically unlikely. Hence combined with some hedges against disaster and as one of many positions in the portfolio, Vega wrote the put.\r\n\r\nSaid put is now trading for around $3.20 and in our view isn’t such a compelling opportunity anymore. The potential returns have fallen considerably and the risks are changing. As options approach maturity, they become more sensitive to market shocks relative to that of options which have more time until expiration. The reason is that if there is a sudden drop in the market, the near term option may go in-the-money and not have ample time for the market price to correct before expiration.\r\n\r\nHowever new opportunities have arisen elsewhere – particularly in the SPY (S&amp;P500 SPDR mini) and we have redeployed capital accordingly.\r\n\r\nVega last week wrote a put option on March 2019 SPY 260 puts for $13.40 (last price was $13.90 so we’re down slightly). We received $1,340 per put and put up around $4,400 in margin per put. The return on capital employed at the time was around 30 per cent with embedded alpha of 5 per cent (at fair value, the option should have only been offering a 25 per cent return).\r\n\r\nOur outlook on the SPY is neutral to positive and this is required for a written put position to yield us a return. The economy in our view is strong (see <a href=\"http://vegacapital.net/2018/04/08/how-does-vega-see-the-us-economic-cycle/\">here</a>), price momentum has weakened (not conclusively) and volatility clustering post the February correction has abated. Now this opportunity is nowhere as good as the QQQ trade prior however with a 30 per cent potential return on capital employed it was a welcome addition to the portfolio.\r\n\r\nIt’s important we clarify however that this trade on the SPY has not been made in isolation, it\'s one part of a much larger portfolio and has been made in conjunction with various hedges. <strong>Hence we’re not advising clients or readers to make the same trade</strong>. As always, please seek the counsel of a licenced professional before making any investment decisions.', 'SPYing an opportunity', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'spying-an-opportunity', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:29:10', '2018-08-23 11:29:10', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/?p=2084', 0, 'post', '', 0);
