(2146, 1, '2018-05-04 00:53:11', '2018-05-04 00:53:11', 'How good is your judgement of probability?\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: How Vega uses probability to outperform\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet’s start with a riddle. Take a coin and a chessboard. This coin fits perfectly within a square on the chessboard. Now if you dropped the coin onto the chessboard, what is the likelihood that the coin covers the corner of four chessboard squares?\r\n\r\nNow intuitively this likelihood would seem to be rather small or large (depending on who you ask). But actually <a href=\"https://www.braingle.com/brainteasers/teaser.php?op=2&amp;id=43993&amp;comm=0\">if you do the math</a>, there’s almost a fair chance of this occurring (47.6 per cent).\r\n\r\nHumans intuitively are poor judges of probability. The economist Robert Shiller regularly takes a survey of investor’s thoughts on the market. One question he asks is for the participants to judge the probability of a catastrophic market crash within the next six months. Now statistically, the likelihood of such an event is about 1 per cent, however over the last 25 years, participants have assigned a 19 per cent mean probability to such an event.\r\n\r\nSo why is this the case? To be fair, probabilities are hard to account for in the market for many reasons.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Market participants are subject to bias – informational, emotional and behavioural.</li>\r\n 	<li>There is not always a standardised method to estimate probability.</li>\r\n 	<li>We are subject to only using a subset of all known information. And new information is coming in all the time.</li>\r\n 	<li>Financial markets are a complex system – the way in which it behaves varies over time.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nLet’s now consider an example a friend asked for my advice on recently and then discuss the approach that Vega would use.\r\n\r\nLet’s say we’re considering buying a security. It is believed that the security will be worth $5.00 if event X occurs, $5.20 if event Y occurs and $3.50 if neither of the two occur (call this event Z). The market mostly believes X will occur and so the security is currently trading for $4.70.\r\n\r\nIt is believed that the market is most probably right (call it 65 per cent chance) but also believed that Y could occur (25 per cent chance). Event Z is viewed as most unlikely although possible (10 per cent chance). The source of these probability estimates is investor\'s experience in the market over time.\r\n\r\nBased on this information, what should we do? Most investors will attempt to calculate the expected profit from each scenario and find the sum total. In this case, the expected profit from such a transaction is 20 cents.\r\n\r\nWe’re ignoring the time component of this trade – obviously if it were to take 1 month, it’s more favourable than if it were to take 1 year. Hence if the duration were short, it might be considered a worthwhile investment. What I want to focus on though is two things.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Unlike in our coin example, we have no reliable way to demonstrate that the probability estimates are accurate. Probabilities based on investor\'s experience in the market (as we can see from Shiller\'s example) can be very wrong.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>The probability estimates are hence based on nothing more than bias and perception. </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNow if the upside cases were to emerge, this matters less - we\'ve made money. But what if the $3.50 case emerged? We don’t wish to make the same mistake that Shiller’s survey participants did in overestimating the risk - but since <strong>we don’t actually know</strong> whether the probability is 1 per cent or 50 per cent or even roughly what it is, it makes sense to consider the downside risk more stringently.\r\n\r\nWe’re also ignoring the fact that making a bet based on probabilities for a scenario which has only 1 step has issues. Whilst the probability of realising the $5.20 case may be 65 per cent, in reality, it either happens or it doesn’t. Many trials are required to make theory a reality.\r\n\r\nVega’s approach would be to pass on such an opportunity - this is unless the duration were sufficiently short, some downside risk could be hedged away and we could more reliably assess the probable outcomes through statistical and economic analysis. Such an approach is the driving force behind Vega’s stellar back test results. As it turns out, being humble pays dividends.\r\n\r\nIn the coming weeks, we’ll be releasing details of our 25 year back test which demonstrates Vega’s strong returns over many bull and bear markets.\r\n\r\n<!-- <fw_preview_session>1525350087701</fw_preview_session> -->', 'How Vega uses probability to outperform', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-vega-uses-probability-to-outperform', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:27:50', '2018-08-23 11:27:50', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/?p=2098', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2147, 1, '2018-05-15 06:05:37', '2018-05-14 20:05:37', '<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Vega\'s first month trading performance\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNo blog for this week however we do wish to inform readers on the Vega Fund\'s first month of live trading performance. The Vega Fund is currently trading with capital provided by the founder and this will be the case until our formal launch date.\r\n\r\nOver the last month, The Vega Fund has generated a 3.3 per cent return. The active risk book contributed 5.2 per cent in performance with the hedging book detracting 1.9 per cent.\r\n\r\nThe S&amp;P500 total return index also generated a 3.3 per cent return.\r\n\r\nWe took advantage of a few volatile days to increase the duration of the portfolio at opportunistic prices. The hedging book was moderated slightly as our risk algorithms became marginally less cautious. Overall this was an uneventful month.\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund is a long term strategy. 3.3 per cent for the first month is certainly pleasing, but negligible relative to performance over the long term.\r\n\r\nWe are currently in the final stages of agreements for administration, AFSL and other standard fund requirements. As such, we\'ve moved our launch date until the 1st of July 2018.<!-- <fw_preview_session>1525932334219</fw_preview_session> -->', 'Vega\'s first month trading performance', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'vegas-first-month-trading-performance', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:26:26', '2018-08-23 11:26:26', '', 0, 'http://vegacapital.net/?p=2124', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2148, 1, '2018-05-18 11:00:11', '2018-05-18 01:00:11', '<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: On interest rates and markets...\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nStandard economic doctrine is to expect that central banks will increase interest rates in order to tame inflation into some prescribed range. The objectives of a central bank may differ somewhat between countries but they generally have a similar approach – rising inflation is contained with higher interest rates and vice versa.\r\n\r\nInflation typically occurs when economies are going a little too well (I’ve clarified with ‘typically’ to exclude events such as Germany’s hyperinflation of the 1920’s and the like). For example, as an economy reaches output capacity it leads to a tighter labour market which spurs wage increases and then more spending/borrowing. Over time, inflation results.\r\n\r\nNow let’s introduce the stock market. A simple valuation model for stocks is the Gordon Growth Model which can be expressed as follows.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2140 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"432\" height=\"56\" />\r\n\r\nThe rate of discount is key here because it’s the sum of (i) the risk free rate (set by the central bank) and (ii) the risk premium. Hence if the central bank raises rates, this places downside pressure on the valuation that the stock market can achieve. Indeed, the Fed has been raising rates and is expected to continue to do so.\r\n\r\nSo should we be worried about lower stock prices in the future ? Well let’s not forget earnings and earnings growth. As noted prior, for interest rates to rise we need excess inflation as a result of an economy which is beginning to overheat. What would we expect in such an environment? Higher earnings. This puts upward pressure on valuations which can offset the downward pressure of interest rates.\r\n\r\n(There are exceptions to this theory but let’s stick to the standard model).\r\n\r\nThis is why despite the uptick in fed rates over the 2004-2008 period, the stock market kept climbing.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2141 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"481\" height=\"289\" />\r\n\r\nNegative returns only result when the economy’s debt burden becomes too heavy, which then requires consumers to cuts spending to pay back their debts (a deleveraging). And which then results in lower income for others (a recession begins).\r\n\r\nSo let\'s bring this framework back to what we\'re seeing in the US economy;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/15/feds-kaplan-sees-us-inflation-rising-but-not-running-away.html\">The Fed see’s inflation as rising but not an issue</a>. This appears to be a fair assessment. This is also why rate increases have been small in nature - there\'s little inflation for the Fed to fight.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2142\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"601\" height=\"289\" />\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Household debt as a function of GDP ($15.6 trillion, 78.7% of GDP) is at subdued levels.</li>\r\n 	<li>Corporate non financial debt ($14.3 trillion, 73.5% of GDP) by the same measure is as high as it was prior to the GFC. Serviceability of said debt is obviously a function of the health of the economy and the magnitude of future interest rate rises – particularly for those companies on the high yield end of the spectrum.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2143\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"603\" height=\"346\" />\r\n\r\nOn the latter there is some cause for concern. Over the coming 5 years, approximately $2 trillion of this debt rolls over. That’s a lot of debt to clear in an environment with increasing interest rates.\r\n\r\nWe’ll be discussing this topic more in the coming weeks.\r\n\r\nIn other news, the Vega Fund is on schedule to be launched on the 1<sup>st</sup> of July 2018. There will be two investment options for investors – one via Interactive Brokers in which an amount of capital may be delegated towards Vega for management. The second is standard whereby investors may purchase units in a unit trust which is administered by a third party.\r\n\r\nEach option will have the same portfolio, returns, fees and other fund characteristics.\r\n\r\nForms and contacts will be placed on the website once our AFSL requirements and administration required are finalised over the next few weeks. If you have any questions about the upcoming launch Vega Fund, please don’t hesitate to contact me.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>If you find the content of our blogs useful, you can now subscribe</em> for <i>weekly updates on investments in the Vega portfolio, market and macroeconomic analysis. </i>', 'On interest rates and markets...', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'on-interest-rates', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:25:24', '2018-08-23 11:25:24', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2139', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2174, 1, '2018-05-30 06:00:17', '2018-05-29 20:00:17', '<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: The Eurozone is back in the news\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nUpon opening my trading screen last night (Tuesday night), the first thing I noticed was that the VIX had spiked up over 30 per cent - an interesting but not unusual occurrence. The reason was market concerns around Italy’s new right wing government – the Five Star party and how it may effect Italy’s finances as well as its standing or even membership of the European Bloc. Some poor results from a couple of US companies didn\'t help either.\r\n\r\nAs of the time of writing, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 1.7 per cent and yet the Vega portfolio was down only 0.25 per cent as a result of our hedges kicking in. It’s actually surprising that such news has had any market impact given that none of this is new information. Further, such events are insignificant in the grand scheme of things.\r\n\r\nYet - since the Vega Fund is in its early stage, I believe it’s worth us commenting on such a topic to explain how the algorithm deals with these issues (which occur commonly) and why our philosophy considers these events as simply noise.\r\n\r\nThere are two main concerns, the first is that Italy will default on its public debt. The second is that Italy will leave the Bloc.\r\n\r\nFirstly the latter raises the risk of the former since it shows that the government is willing to engage in radical measures to achieve its goals. Italy will likely pay higher interest rates on future debt issues outside of the Bloc than inside it which increases default prospects. But remember, a big funder of the Italian debt is Italian citizens – which would mean that Italy essentially defaults on itself – an odd conundrum.\r\n\r\nItaly has an economy operating with debt levels of more than 130 per cent of GDP. This makes life difficult because if interest rates are say 3 per cent, it’s interest bill per annum is higher than GDP growth and to escape from this requires large cuts in spending (austerity) – of which we know creates a weak/recessionary economy and makes the prospect of growth hard to achieve.\r\n\r\nTo bring this back to Vega’s algorithm and how it handles such events, at this stage we would need to see it create a significant amount of trade destabilisation which then precipitates into a more broad-based global economic contraction and unemployment.\r\n\r\nSince today’s events are not likely to impact these variables so significantly, we can see why Vega’s algorithm would largely ignore it - hence our portfolio is still long market exposure.\r\n\r\nThis is similar to what the back test results showed when Greece was in the news – a lot of noise, but little real risk.', 'The Eurozone is back in the news', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-eurozone-is-back-in-the-news', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:24:36', '2018-08-23 11:24:36', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2174', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2576, 1, '2018-06-12 10:02:17', '2018-06-12 00:02:17', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Vega’s 2nd month of returns\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Over the past week we have been overhauling the site layout and adding new content prior to the launch of the fund. If you experience any issues viewing or using our website, please don’t hesitate to let us know. </em>\r\n\r\nOver the Fund’s 2<sup>nd</sup> month of trading, the strategy generated a 2.4 per cent return. The portfolio was largely flat until we saw profits from Italy’s economic and political woes rising (again) followed by a strong unemployment number out of the US. President Trump’s imposition of trade tariffs were a detractor but a minor one at that.\r\n\r\nOur benchmark (the S&amp;P500 total return index) generated a 3.3 per cent return hence beating the Vega Fund’s performance by 0.9 per cent. This is not an unusual occurrence for the fund over short term time horizons – sometimes the index does run ahead. However over the medium term and longer term, the Vega fund has a strong tendency to catch up as shown in the back test results.\r\n\r\nVega’s active risk book generated a 5.9 per cent return whilst our hedging book detracted 3.5 per cent, largely due to front month June VIX futures falling from 15.6 to 13.35.\r\n\r\nCumulatively since inception, the strategy is up 5.77 per cent.\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund will be formally opened on the 1<sup>st</sup> of July 2018 to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Our information memorandum and application forms will be posted on the website shortly.\r\n\r\nIf you are interested in becoming a foundation investor of the Vega Fund, please contact us at the link above.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Vega’s 2nd month of returns – 2.4 per cent', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'vegas-2nd-month-of-returns-2-4-per-cent', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:23:12', '2018-08-23 11:23:12', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2576', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2587, 1, '2018-06-14 06:00:58', '2018-06-13 20:00:58', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Tariffs...why?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nToday I want to discuss the economic implications of tariffs and why they are a point of concern.\r\n\r\nWhether you agree with President Trump or not, his intentions aren’t terrible. His view is that other countries are engaging in unfair trading practices which impact Americans in an adverse way.\r\n\r\nAnd the truth is that yes – competition from cheaper resources or labour from overseas does impact some workers negatively. This is not something we can dismiss because it’s real people, not just statistics that we’re talking about.\r\n\r\nHowever when formulating policy, there’s no reason not to engage in practices which vastly improve the quality of life outcomes for the majority of the populous. Programs and policies can be devised and funded to support the less fortunate however it’s up to the government to ensure that they’re executed well.\r\n\r\nNow what benefits am I talking about? Well there are many but I want to draw attention to just one – wealth. Consider the last several hundred years since the beginning of the industrial revolution. What is noticeable is the vast improvement in the wealth state of all citizens. It’s been the greatest upheaval of citizens from poverty to prosperity that has ever occurred in human history.\r\n\r\nThrough technology and practices, we’ve enable our society to become infinitely more productive i.e. producing more goods &amp; services and hence enjoy a higher quality of life.\r\n\r\nTariffs are a reversal of that trend – it\'s taking value from both consumers and producers by artificially inflating the price of goods and services and transferring that value to the government. The consumer budget becomes more stretched, producers are less incentivised to compete (especially tariff protected producers) and there’s less money left for innovation and product/service improvements.\r\n\r\nThis is even before we consider the adverse effects of the government essentially picking winners and losers in the market place.\r\n\r\nThe costs of a tariff are not equally spread however – obviously if you are a tariff protected producer then you don’t have a cost – in fact you get a benefit. However consumers of imported products in competition with the local producers obviously lose. In addition, jobs which depend on prior low prices of the tariff protected product lose out and this can be a much larger population than of those said tariff was originally trying to protect.\r\n\r\nFor example, whilst steel tariff may benefit steel producers, they hurt car manufacturers and other businesses which do better with low steel prices. Hence whilst you might save some jobs within the steel producing industries, you lose jobs elsewhere which damages the economy on a net basis.\r\n\r\nThe derivative effect of tariffs of course is that other countries retaliate which compounds the problem (and which is now occurring). You end up in a tit-for-tat of tariff trading which benefits a few at the expense of the many. It’s a wealth reducing set of circumstances which would have negative outcomes for both economies and markets.\r\n\r\nAt Vega, we don’t believe that this is something which is likely to result in hugely adverse consequences for the market unless President Trump makes a habit of such measures – unfortunately there is a small probability that he may well do.\r\n\r\nInvestors should know however that if a tariff war were to begin to impact the US economy, our algorithms which monitor this data will act - aiming to both minimise the downside risk and maximise the upside potential.\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund will be formally opened on the 1<sup>st</sup> of July 2018 to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Our information memorandum and application forms will be posted on the website shortly.\r\n\r\nIf you are interested in becoming a foundation investor of the Vega Fund, please contact us at the link above.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Tariffs….why?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'tariffs-why', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:21:51', '2018-08-23 11:21:51', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2587', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2625, 1, '2018-06-18 06:00:12', '2018-06-17 20:00:12', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Vega opens to seed investors\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe\'re delighted to announce the Vega Fund has begun accepting applications from sophisticated and wholesale investors pursuant to its 1 July 2018 launch.\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund is a long term strategy which employs derivatives to generate high returns regardless of whether the market moves up or down. For a more comprehensive review of our strategy, please read the disclosures provided within our Information Memorandum in the link <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/invest/\">‘Invest in Vega’</a>. Our Application Form can also be found in the same link.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to see our live performance to date, <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/performance/\">please click here</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'The Vega Fund opens to seed investors', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-vega-fund-opens-to-seed-investors', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:19:35', '2018-08-23 11:19:35', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2625', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2628, 1, '2018-06-21 07:00:45', '2018-06-20 21:00:45', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Tariffs…Why? Part 2\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMany would by now know about President Trump’s escalation of trade tensions between the US and other economic powers of the world. Let’s start off today’s blog by putting some numbers around the topic.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.census.gov/foreign-trade/statistics/historical/gands.pdf\">According to Census.gov</a>, US imported goods and services were valued at $2.9 trillion in 2017. China exports to the US were circa $500 billion hence meaning that Chinese exports comprised 17 per cent of US imports – clearly not a small number.\r\n\r\nUS exports of goods and services to China are valued at $120/$130 billion resulting in a trade deficit of approximately $380 billion in favour of China.\r\n\r\nEarlier last week, the Trump Administration put forth a plan to place tariffs across $46.2b of Chinese exports to the US. China responded with its own tariffs across $49.8b of US exports to which President Trump retaliated with a plan for tariffs accross an additional $200b goods and services as well the threat of another $200b if they retaliated again.\r\n\r\nThe below info-graphic (compiled by Chad P Bown of the Peterson Institute for International Economics) gives us an idea about what exports are affected prior to Trumps escalation of $200b of tariffed Chinese exports.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2630\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/pic-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"284\" height=\"369\" /> <img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2631\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/pic-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"306\" height=\"369\" />\r\n\r\nSummed up, the Presidents threats now comprise circa 90 per cent of China’s exports to the US - approximately 15.5 per cent of total US imports.\r\n\r\nAs we discussed in our <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/2018/06/14/tariffs-why/\">previous blog</a>, the impact is not just on the producers of the tariff protected goods – it’s on all the downstream producers/services relying on that good. Hence the cost of these tariffs can be very widespread. In addition, most economists would agree that the costs of a tariff outweigh the benefits gained by the protected goods and services.\r\n\r\nAdd on top of this the fact that the President is also pushing tariffs onto Mexico, Canada and the European Union….who are in turn retaliating with their own tariffs over many billions of US exports.\r\n\r\nThe economic benefits which accrue to nations as a result of free trade are quite well known – hence all these actions seem very irrational and many suspect that this is less of a real threat by the President and is more posturing. Time will tell.\r\n\r\nChina of course can’t retaliate with its own tariff of $200b because the US isn\'t exporting that much to them. But it can attempt to make the US\' agenda in Asia more complicated. North Korea or The South China Sea would seem the obvious choices from that angle. It doesn’t appear likely however that China will be able to back down since the President has given them no face-saving way of accomplishing this feat.\r\n\r\nThe President however can back down and whilst many believe that that he’s too stubborn for this, I’m less sure. President Trump often has a more…fluid approach to policy making and we might be having a very different conversation by next month (or next week).\r\n\r\nThe most sensible option at this point would be for China and the US to meet, curb tensions and have both sides walk away declaring victory. However unlikely this scenario seems at this hour, its realisation wouldn’t surprise me.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, if these issues continue to escalate, (in my own view) it just might be enough to impair the economic growth of the US over the short to medium term which would likely have a negative impact on financial markets.\r\n\r\nThe Vega portfolio doesn’t operate via ‘views’ however – as it stands the Vega economic algorithms are bullish, hence so is the portfolio and despite stock markets falling over the past couple of days, the portfolio is holding up quite well via it\'s hedging book. Our algorithms continue to monitor economic data and will make any required changes accordingly.\r\n\r\nAs an aside, if economic growth does become impaired over the medium term, our back tests have shown that such an occurrence is one in which the Vega portfolio can perform exceptionally well.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Tariffs…Why? Part 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'tariffswhy-part-2', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:18:20', '2018-08-23 11:18:20', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2628', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2648, 1, '2018-07-11 10:29:06', '2018-07-11 00:29:06', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Vega’s 1st quarter returns\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOver the Fund’s 1<sup>st</sup> quarter of trading, we experienced relatively mild trading conditions and have delivered a 5.7 per cent return. Our active risk positions generated a 14 per cent return and hedging positions detracted 8.3 per cent – netting 5.7 per cent.\r\n\r\nSince we’re finishing a quarter, it’s worth a brief review of what we’re observing in the US economy and comment on how Vega is positioning itself.\r\n\r\nWe’ll first start on tariffs. For those just catching up – we previously blogged about tariffs <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/2018/06/21/tariffswhy-part-2/\">here</a>. These are a concern since if President Trump were to follow through on his threats to further expand tariffs to include all Chinese exports, this significantly increases the probability that the US will go into a recession.\r\n\r\nAs this occurs, the Vega Fund will likely begin to reposition itself from being bullish to bearish. It’s apparent that in such a circumstance that neither the US Government nor the Federal Reserve will have the firepower necessary to combat such an issue with stimulus. Further, prices for stocks appear high and given that the authorities have little in reserve should something go wrong, the downside is likely quite large.\r\n\r\nThis presents a very rare opportunity for the Vega Fund to generate outsized returns.  We can’t say with certainty that it will occur – only that our algorithms will be monitoring closely.\r\n\r\nNot all we’re seeing is bad news and notably the fund has still been positioned long (with hedges in place). Over the last quarter, US employment numbers have been not been stronger for over 16 years.\r\n\r\nThe unemployment rate in June increased to 4.0 per cent from 3.8 per cent back in May as a result of a 600,000 increase in the number of citizens seeking work. It will be interesting to see how they fair over the next month.\r\n\r\nInterest rates still appear cyclically low despite having quite a hawkish Federal Reserve board. As many have observed, if we were to quote an unemployment rate of 4.0 per cent, the S&amp;P500 at record highs, inflation at 2.8 per cent, where would we expect interest rates? Certainly higher than 2 per cent....\r\n\r\nIn 2015, 2016 and 2017 it was understandable that the Fed wouldn’t raise rates too quickly because inflation was tempered. However now it has to temper raising so as not to elevate systemic risks given how much debt has been issued by corporates.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2649 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/pic-3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"602\" height=\"352\" />\r\n\r\nTempering would also be required should tariffs begin to have a negative impact on economic growth. As such, it could still be a while before we reach a more normal interest rate environment.\r\n\r\nFinally, the Vega Fund has now formally launched and is open to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Qualified investors may find our Information Memorandum and Application Form <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/invest/\">here</a> however if you would like a hard copy mailed to you, please don’t hesitate to contact our office on 1800 960 707.', 'Vega’s 1st quarter return +5.7 per cent', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'vegas-1st-quarter-return-5-7-per-cent', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:17:00', '2018-08-23 11:17:00', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2648', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2671, 1, '2018-07-12 07:00:17', '2018-07-11 21:00:17', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Profiting from downside risk\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEarlier this week we reported our performance for the quarter (+5.7 per cent). We also broke this number down into returns from our active risk positions (+14 per cent) and our hedging book (-8.3 per cent).\r\n\r\nNaturally, investors may wonder why hedging is required when it’s clearly so costly. After all, if we didn’t hedge, we could deliver much higher returns. But this is only true if nothing goes wrong. The benefit of hedging occurs when things do go wrong.\r\n\r\nSo today we’re going to run some simulations to see the benefit of Vega’s hedging algorithm.\r\n\r\nLet’s run the Vega strategy on some historical data using just SPY puts with a duration of 12 to 18 months. We’re firstly not going to hedge in order to see how volatile the portfolio’s performance gets and emphasise the value of hedging.\r\n\r\nThe period we’re going to test over is the first half of FY11. Over this period, the US lost its AAA credit rating which caused a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Monday_(2011)\">minor panic in the markets</a>.\r\n\r\nTo start, here’s how the index did over that period.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2674 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/hedge-pic-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"481\" height=\"289\" />\r\n\r\nAs above, the SPY declined by 6.3 per cent. At its worst it was down 18.8 per cent. Annualised volatility was 30 per cent – clearly a rough patch.\r\n\r\nVega’s portfolio at this time would have been long market exposure due to the strengthening economy and expensive put option prices. Clearly with the index falling from 135 to 110, a portfolio of written puts is going to fare quite badly but this is what Vega would have had.\r\n\r\nSo let’s look at how Vega performed <strong>without</strong> the hedging algorithm.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2675 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/hedge-pic-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"481\" height=\"289\" />\r\n\r\nIn short – not well. The strategy lost 6.1 per cent for the half, what was worse however was the &gt; 40 per cent drawdown incurred. Annualised volatility for the period was a gut wrenching 77 per cent. Quite clearly, this is not an experience we would hope to incur in the Vega portfolio.\r\n\r\nThe index lost 6.3 per cent so technically the strategy outperformed. However at Vega we don’t consider a negative return as outperformance – even if it beats the index.\r\n\r\nNow let’s <strong>add back in</strong> the hedging algorithm and see how Vega performs.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2677 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/hedge-pic-3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"481\" height=\"289\" />\r\n\r\nWhat a difference! By using the hedging book, the strategy is able to hold on during the market collapse and then also capture the upside from the recovery. There’s still a draw-down of 16.4 per cent and elevated volatility of 43 per cent (annualised) however Vega returned 21.7 per cent over the period – outperforming by 28 per cent.\r\n\r\nThe value of hedging is hence very apparent. Vega can generate strong returns in bull markets even if hedging is expensive and this is a good trade off to ensure it can generate returns in weaker markets.\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund has now formally launched and is open to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Qualified investors may find our Information Memorandum and Application Form <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/invest/\">here</a> however if you would like a hard copy mailed to you, please don’t hesitate to contact our office on 1800 960 707.', 'Profiting from downside risk', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'profiting-from-downside-risk', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:14:58', '2018-08-23 11:14:58', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2671', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2688, 1, '2018-07-16 16:00:58', '2018-07-16 06:00:58', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Insights into Vega’s algorithm – the GFC\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\nLast week I wrote a blog about Vega’s hedging algorithm – the response was great and I appreciated the positive feedback a lot.\r\n\r\nSince investors are keen to learn more about how Vega can deliver downside protection, I thought it would be valuable to show a simulation of our strategy over the GFC during 2008. This is notably where Vega has the potential to really shine.\r\n\r\nLet’s start by looking at the SPY. The index began 2008 at circa 145 and capitulated 38.6 per cent over the year to below 89. Annualised volatility was 41.3 per cent for this period. This was one of the worst markets for investors since the Great Depression.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2692 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/hedge-pic-4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"447\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nAnd admittedly, if it weren’t for the actions of The Federal Reserve, The US Treasury and many members of the exiting Bush Administration and entering Obama Administration, it might well have been the Second Great Depression. I always credit Ben Bernanke, Timothy Geithner, Hank Paulson and President Barrack Obama in particular for their huge roles in stabilising the Global Financial System at this time.\r\n\r\nSo let’s see how Vega would have performed over this period using SPY put options with a duration of 6 to 12 months.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2693 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/hedge-pic-5.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"467\" height=\"282\" />\r\n\r\nThe returns are clearly large...so what happened? In the simulation, Vega during 2007 had been long market exposure through writing put options across various market indices. By late in 2007, it had liquidated all its positions into cash. In late April of of 2008, it began buying puts and also entered into some hedges.\r\n\r\nBy year end, the simulation results show that Vega would have generated a 142 per cent return on capital employed. Versus the index, this represents circa 180 percentage points of out-performance. Annualised volatility was rather high at 55 per cent, however this is a small price to pay for such a high return. In addition, the strategy was rather inefficient between October and December and had some rough draw-downs, although not as bad as what the SPY would have experienced over the year.\r\n\r\nOverall, if this were the result of our portfolio over this timeframe, we’d be quite pleased. <strong>But please note a few important points to consider upon reviewing these performance numbers.</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>The simulation is limited in nature. We’ve only run it on SPY puts of a certain duration at a single strike for the purposes of a blog. Other positions on other assets and strike prices may have generated lesser returns.</li>\r\n 	<li>The simulation was done on a portfolio of long SPY put options. In future we’ll most likely have the algorithm use <a href=\"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/b/bearputspread.asp\">bear put spreads</a> to achieve high returns but with lower downside risk to reduce the impact if our models were to be wrong.</li>\r\n 	<li>Past performance does not equal a promise of future returns. The GFC was a very volatile event and in the simulation Vega was able to capture the downside well. Yet future crises may be less severe which would obviously mean the potential for returns is lesser.</li>\r\n 	<li>Events like this don’t occur every year. We expect Vega to do well but certainly not earn more than 100 per cent annually.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOur mandate at Vega Capital is to invest our client’s investment in such a way as to generate high returns during both expansions and contractions in the economy and financial markets. This means that for sophisticated clients, our offering can help buffer the negative impact of a large financial crash to an investment portfolio as well as generating high returns in better times.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund has now formally launched and is open to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Qualified investors may find our Information Memorandum and Application Form <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/invest/\">here</a> however if you would like a hard copy mailed to you, please don’t hesitate to contact our office on 1800 960 707.\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Insights into Vega’s algorithm – the GFC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'insights-into-vegas-algorithm-the-gfc', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:13:53', '2018-08-23 11:13:53', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2688', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(2707, 1, '2018-07-24 06:45:41', '2018-07-23 20:45:41', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Options trading over July\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\nToday’s blog is quite short but we have a few announcements.\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>I’m delighted to announce that we are intending to showcase The Vega Fund in Perth at Startcon’s ‘Pitch for $1 million’ competition on the 31<sup>st</sup> of August 2018. We’re looking forward to fielding questions from investors about the markets, our portfolio and the business itself.</li>\r\n 	<li>I will also be meeting with Sarah Harding of WY Advice for her popular ‘Wealth Wednesdays’ segment in early August. We’ll post a copy of the video on the blog for readers as soon as it’s available.</li>\r\n 	<li>Finally, in addition to publishing weekly on this blog, we will also be publishing new regular content on Livewire.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nToday we’re providing a brief update on some trading and the portfolio\'s positioning. Last week we rolled part of the portfolio which held some QQQ index puts opened back in May and redeployed capital by writing SPY index puts.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund has two conditions in its algorithm which allow for rolling,\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Roll any option with less than 6 months to maturity; or</li>\r\n 	<li>Roll any option whose premium has collapsed significantly in value such that there are better opportunities elsewhere.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nFor the QQQ index puts, we received $787 per contract and bought them back for $240 per contract. We’ve then rolled into some 265 strike December 2019 puts on the SPY index for $1,344 per contract. These appear 5 per cent mispriced and offer a total 23.5 per cent per annum return on capital.\r\n\r\nSince inception our fund has been bullish on the market and this has paid off. Macroeconomic indicators are green and so is momentum hence we’re still comfortable with our long market exposure. We do however have an array of hedges in place going into August to take advantage of any shocks from tariffs or the US reporting season.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund has now formally launched and is open to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Qualified investors may find our Information Memorandum and Application Form <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/invest/\">here</a> however if you would like a hard copy mailed to you, please don’t hesitate to contact our office on 1800 960 707.\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Options trading over July', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'options-trading-over-july', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:12:09', '2018-08-23 11:12:09', '', 0, 'https://vegacapital.net/?p=2707', 0, 'post', '', 0);
