(2790, 1, '2018-08-23 11:18:20', '2018-08-23 11:18:20', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Tariffs…Why? Part 2\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMany would by now know about President Trump’s escalation of trade tensions between the US and other economic powers of the world. Let’s start off today’s blog by putting some numbers around the topic.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.census.gov/foreign-trade/statistics/historical/gands.pdf\">According to Census.gov</a>, US imported goods and services were valued at $2.9 trillion in 2017. China exports to the US were circa $500 billion hence meaning that Chinese exports comprised 17 per cent of US imports – clearly not a small number.\r\n\r\nUS exports of goods and services to China are valued at $120/$130 billion resulting in a trade deficit of approximately $380 billion in favour of China.\r\n\r\nEarlier last week, the Trump Administration put forth a plan to place tariffs across $46.2b of Chinese exports to the US. China responded with its own tariffs across $49.8b of US exports to which President Trump retaliated with a plan for tariffs accross an additional $200b goods and services as well the threat of another $200b if they retaliated again.\r\n\r\nThe below info-graphic (compiled by Chad P Bown of the Peterson Institute for International Economics) gives us an idea about what exports are affected prior to Trumps escalation of $200b of tariffed Chinese exports.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2630\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/pic-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"284\" height=\"369\" /> <img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2631\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/pic-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"306\" height=\"369\" />\r\n\r\nSummed up, the Presidents threats now comprise circa 90 per cent of China’s exports to the US - approximately 15.5 per cent of total US imports.\r\n\r\nAs we discussed in our <a href=\"https://vegacapital.net/2018/06/14/tariffs-why/\">previous blog</a>, the impact is not just on the producers of the tariff protected goods – it’s on all the downstream producers/services relying on that good. Hence the cost of these tariffs can be very widespread. In addition, most economists would agree that the costs of a tariff outweigh the benefits gained by the protected goods and services.\r\n\r\nAdd on top of this the fact that the President is also pushing tariffs onto Mexico, Canada and the European Union….who are in turn retaliating with their own tariffs over many billions of US exports.\r\n\r\nThe economic benefits which accrue to nations as a result of free trade are quite well known – hence all these actions seem very irrational and many suspect that this is less of a real threat by the President and is more posturing. Time will tell.\r\n\r\nChina of course can’t retaliate with its own tariff of $200b because the US isn\'t exporting that much to them. But it can attempt to make the US\' agenda in Asia more complicated. North Korea or The South China Sea would seem the obvious choices from that angle. It doesn’t appear likely however that China will be able to back down since the President has given them no face-saving way of accomplishing this feat.\r\n\r\nThe President however can back down and whilst many believe that that he’s too stubborn for this, I’m less sure. President Trump often has a more…fluid approach to policy making and we might be having a very different conversation by next month (or next week).\r\n\r\nThe most sensible option at this point would be for China and the US to meet, curb tensions and have both sides walk away declaring victory. However unlikely this scenario seems at this hour, its realisation wouldn’t surprise me.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, if these issues continue to escalate, (in my own view) it just might be enough to impair the economic growth of the US over the short to medium term which would likely have a negative impact on financial markets.\r\n\r\nThe Vega portfolio doesn’t operate via ‘views’ however – as it stands the Vega economic algorithms are bullish, hence so is the portfolio and despite stock markets falling over the past couple of days, the portfolio is holding up quite well via it\'s hedging book. Our algorithms continue to monitor economic data and will make any required changes accordingly.\r\n\r\nAs an aside, if economic growth does become impaired over the medium term, our back tests have shown that such an occurrence is one in which the Vega portfolio can perform exceptionally well.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Tariffs…Why? Part 2', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2628-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:18:20', '2018-08-23 11:18:20', '', 2628, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2628-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
