(2794, 1, '2018-08-23 11:21:51', '2018-08-23 11:21:51', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Tariffs...why?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nToday I want to discuss the economic implications of tariffs and why they are a point of concern.\r\n\r\nWhether you agree with President Trump or not, his intentions aren’t terrible. His view is that other countries are engaging in unfair trading practices which impact Americans in an adverse way.\r\n\r\nAnd the truth is that yes – competition from cheaper resources or labour from overseas does impact some workers negatively. This is not something we can dismiss because it’s real people, not just statistics that we’re talking about.\r\n\r\nHowever when formulating policy, there’s no reason not to engage in practices which vastly improve the quality of life outcomes for the majority of the populous. Programs and policies can be devised and funded to support the less fortunate however it’s up to the government to ensure that they’re executed well.\r\n\r\nNow what benefits am I talking about? Well there are many but I want to draw attention to just one – wealth. Consider the last several hundred years since the beginning of the industrial revolution. What is noticeable is the vast improvement in the wealth state of all citizens. It’s been the greatest upheaval of citizens from poverty to prosperity that has ever occurred in human history.\r\n\r\nThrough technology and practices, we’ve enable our society to become infinitely more productive i.e. producing more goods &amp; services and hence enjoy a higher quality of life.\r\n\r\nTariffs are a reversal of that trend – it\'s taking value from both consumers and producers by artificially inflating the price of goods and services and transferring that value to the government. The consumer budget becomes more stretched, producers are less incentivised to compete (especially tariff protected producers) and there’s less money left for innovation and product/service improvements.\r\n\r\nThis is even before we consider the adverse effects of the government essentially picking winners and losers in the market place.\r\n\r\nThe costs of a tariff are not equally spread however – obviously if you are a tariff protected producer then you don’t have a cost – in fact you get a benefit. However consumers of imported products in competition with the local producers obviously lose. In addition, jobs which depend on prior low prices of the tariff protected product lose out and this can be a much larger population than of those said tariff was originally trying to protect.\r\n\r\nFor example, whilst steel tariff may benefit steel producers, they hurt car manufacturers and other businesses which do better with low steel prices. Hence whilst you might save some jobs within the steel producing industries, you lose jobs elsewhere which damages the economy on a net basis.\r\n\r\nThe derivative effect of tariffs of course is that other countries retaliate which compounds the problem (and which is now occurring). You end up in a tit-for-tat of tariff trading which benefits a few at the expense of the many. It’s a wealth reducing set of circumstances which would have negative outcomes for both economies and markets.\r\n\r\nAt Vega, we don’t believe that this is something which is likely to result in hugely adverse consequences for the market unless President Trump makes a habit of such measures – unfortunately there is a small probability that he may well do.\r\n\r\nInvestors should know however that if a tariff war were to begin to impact the US economy, our algorithms which monitor this data will act - aiming to both minimise the downside risk and maximise the upside potential.\r\n\r\nThe Vega Fund will be formally opened on the 1<sup>st</sup> of July 2018 to sophisticated and wholesale investors. Our information memorandum and application forms will be posted on the website shortly.\r\n\r\nIf you are interested in becoming a foundation investor of the Vega Fund, please contact us at the link above.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Vega Capital is a Corporate Authorised Representative (No. 001264482) of Alpha Securities Pty Ltd (ACN 124 327 064) AFS Licence No. 330757.</em>', 'Tariffs….why?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2587-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:21:51', '2018-08-23 11:21:51', '', 2587, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2587-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
