(2798, 1, '2018-08-23 11:24:36', '2018-08-23 11:24:36', '<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: The Eurozone is back in the news\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nUpon opening my trading screen last night (Tuesday night), the first thing I noticed was that the VIX had spiked up over 30 per cent - an interesting but not unusual occurrence. The reason was market concerns around Italy’s new right wing government – the Five Star party and how it may effect Italy’s finances as well as its standing or even membership of the European Bloc. Some poor results from a couple of US companies didn\'t help either.\r\n\r\nAs of the time of writing, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 1.7 per cent and yet the Vega portfolio was down only 0.25 per cent as a result of our hedges kicking in. It’s actually surprising that such news has had any market impact given that none of this is new information. Further, such events are insignificant in the grand scheme of things.\r\n\r\nYet - since the Vega Fund is in its early stage, I believe it’s worth us commenting on such a topic to explain how the algorithm deals with these issues (which occur commonly) and why our philosophy considers these events as simply noise.\r\n\r\nThere are two main concerns, the first is that Italy will default on its public debt. The second is that Italy will leave the Bloc.\r\n\r\nFirstly the latter raises the risk of the former since it shows that the government is willing to engage in radical measures to achieve its goals. Italy will likely pay higher interest rates on future debt issues outside of the Bloc than inside it which increases default prospects. But remember, a big funder of the Italian debt is Italian citizens – which would mean that Italy essentially defaults on itself – an odd conundrum.\r\n\r\nItaly has an economy operating with debt levels of more than 130 per cent of GDP. This makes life difficult because if interest rates are say 3 per cent, it’s interest bill per annum is higher than GDP growth and to escape from this requires large cuts in spending (austerity) – of which we know creates a weak/recessionary economy and makes the prospect of growth hard to achieve.\r\n\r\nTo bring this back to Vega’s algorithm and how it handles such events, at this stage we would need to see it create a significant amount of trade destabilisation which then precipitates into a more broad-based global economic contraction and unemployment.\r\n\r\nSince today’s events are not likely to impact these variables so significantly, we can see why Vega’s algorithm would largely ignore it - hence our portfolio is still long market exposure.\r\n\r\nThis is similar to what the back test results showed when Greece was in the news – a lot of noise, but little real risk.', 'The Eurozone is back in the news', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2174-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:24:36', '2018-08-23 11:24:36', '', 2174, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2174-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2799, 1, '2018-08-23 11:24:43', '2018-08-23 11:24:43', '<!--more-->\n\n<hr />\n\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\nSubject: On interest rates and markets...\n\n<hr />\n\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nStandard economic doctrine is to expect that central banks will increase interest rates in order to tame inflation into some prescribed range. The objectives of a central bank may differ somewhat between countries but they generally have a similar approach – rising inflation is contained with higher interest rates and vice versa.\n\nInflation typically occurs when economies are going a little too well (I’ve clarified with ‘typically’ to exclude events such as Germany’s hyperinflation of the 1920’s and the like). For example, as an economy reaches output capacity it leads to a tighter labour market which spurs wage increases and then more spending/borrowing. Over time, inflation results.\n\nNow let’s introduce the stock market. A simple valuation model for stocks is the Gordon Growth Model which can be expressed as follows.\n\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2140 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"432\" height=\"56\" />\n\nThe rate of discount is key here because it’s the sum of (i) the risk free rate (set by the central bank) and (ii) the risk premium. Hence if the central bank raises rates, this places downside pressure on the valuation that the stock market can achieve. Indeed, the Fed has been raising rates and is expected to continue to do so.\n\nSo should we be worried about lower stock prices in the future ? Well let’s not forget earnings and earnings growth. As noted prior, for interest rates to rise we need excess inflation as a result of an economy which is beginning to overheat. What would we expect in such an environment? Higher earnings. This puts upward pressure on valuations which can offset the downward pressure of interest rates.\n\n(There are exceptions to this theory but let’s stick to the standard model).\n\nThis is why despite the uptick in fed rates over the 2004-2008 period, the stock market kept climbing.\n\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-2141 aligncenter\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"481\" height=\"289\" />\n\nNegative returns only result when the economy’s debt burden becomes too heavy, which then requires consumers to cuts spending to pay back their debts (a deleveraging). And which then results in lower income for others (a recession begins).\n\nSo let\'s bring this framework back to what we\'re seeing in the US economy;\n<ul>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/15/feds-kaplan-sees-us-inflation-rising-but-not-running-away.html\">The Fed see’s inflation as rising but not an issue</a>. This appears to be a fair assessment. This is also why rate increases have been small in nature - there\'s little inflation for the Fed to fight.</li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2142\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"601\" height=\"289\" />\n<ul>\n 	<li>Household debt as a function of GDP ($15.6 trillion, 78.7% of GDP) is at subdued levels.</li>\n 	<li>Corporate non financial debt ($14.3 trillion, 73.5% of GDP) by the same measure is as high as it was prior to the GFC. Serviceability of said debt is obviously a function of the health of the economy and the magnitude of future interest rate rises – particularly for those companies on the high yield end of the spectrum.</li>\n</ul>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2143\" src=\"https://vegacapital.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Econ-pic-4.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"603\" height=\"346\" />\n\nOn the latter there is some cause for concern. Over the coming 5 years, approximately $2 trillion of this debt rolls over. That’s a lot of debt to clear in an environment with increasing interest rates.\n\nWe’ll be discussing this topic more in the coming weeks.\n\nIn other news, the Vega Fund is on schedule to be launched on the 1<sup>st</sup> of July 2018. There will be two investment options for investors – one via Interactive Brokers in which an amount of capital may be delegated towards Vega for management. The second is standard whereby investors may purchase units in a unit trust which is administered by a third party.\n\nEach option will have the same portfolio, returns, fees and other fund characteristics.\n\nForms and contacts will be placed on the website once our AFSL requirements and administration required are finalised over the next few weeks. If you have any questions about the upcoming launch Vega Fund, please don’t hesitate to contact me.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>If you find the content of our blogs useful, you can now subscribe</em> for <i>weekly updates on investments in the Vega portfolio, market and macroeconomic analysis. </i>', 'On interest rates and markets...', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2148-autosave-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:24:43', '2018-08-23 11:24:43', '', 2148, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2148-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
