(2805, 1, '2018-08-23 11:27:50', '2018-08-23 11:27:50', 'How good is your judgement of probability?\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: How Vega uses probability to outperform\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet’s start with a riddle. Take a coin and a chessboard. This coin fits perfectly within a square on the chessboard. Now if you dropped the coin onto the chessboard, what is the likelihood that the coin covers the corner of four chessboard squares?\r\n\r\nNow intuitively this likelihood would seem to be rather small or large (depending on who you ask). But actually <a href=\"https://www.braingle.com/brainteasers/teaser.php?op=2&amp;id=43993&amp;comm=0\">if you do the math</a>, there’s almost a fair chance of this occurring (47.6 per cent).\r\n\r\nHumans intuitively are poor judges of probability. The economist Robert Shiller regularly takes a survey of investor’s thoughts on the market. One question he asks is for the participants to judge the probability of a catastrophic market crash within the next six months. Now statistically, the likelihood of such an event is about 1 per cent, however over the last 25 years, participants have assigned a 19 per cent mean probability to such an event.\r\n\r\nSo why is this the case? To be fair, probabilities are hard to account for in the market for many reasons.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Market participants are subject to bias – informational, emotional and behavioural.</li>\r\n 	<li>There is not always a standardised method to estimate probability.</li>\r\n 	<li>We are subject to only using a subset of all known information. And new information is coming in all the time.</li>\r\n 	<li>Financial markets are a complex system – the way in which it behaves varies over time.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nLet’s now consider an example a friend asked for my advice on recently and then discuss the approach that Vega would use.\r\n\r\nLet’s say we’re considering buying a security. It is believed that the security will be worth $5.00 if event X occurs, $5.20 if event Y occurs and $3.50 if neither of the two occur (call this event Z). The market mostly believes X will occur and so the security is currently trading for $4.70.\r\n\r\nIt is believed that the market is most probably right (call it 65 per cent chance) but also believed that Y could occur (25 per cent chance). Event Z is viewed as most unlikely although possible (10 per cent chance). The source of these probability estimates is investor\'s experience in the market over time.\r\n\r\nBased on this information, what should we do? Most investors will attempt to calculate the expected profit from each scenario and find the sum total. In this case, the expected profit from such a transaction is 20 cents.\r\n\r\nWe’re ignoring the time component of this trade – obviously if it were to take 1 month, it’s more favourable than if it were to take 1 year. Hence if the duration were short, it might be considered a worthwhile investment. What I want to focus on though is two things.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Unlike in our coin example, we have no reliable way to demonstrate that the probability estimates are accurate. Probabilities based on investor\'s experience in the market (as we can see from Shiller\'s example) can be very wrong.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>The probability estimates are hence based on nothing more than bias and perception. </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nNow if the upside cases were to emerge, this matters less - we\'ve made money. But what if the $3.50 case emerged? We don’t wish to make the same mistake that Shiller’s survey participants did in overestimating the risk - but since <strong>we don’t actually know</strong> whether the probability is 1 per cent or 50 per cent or even roughly what it is, it makes sense to consider the downside risk more stringently.\r\n\r\nWe’re also ignoring the fact that making a bet based on probabilities for a scenario which has only 1 step has issues. Whilst the probability of realising the $5.20 case may be 65 per cent, in reality, it either happens or it doesn’t. Many trials are required to make theory a reality.\r\n\r\nVega’s approach would be to pass on such an opportunity - this is unless the duration were sufficiently short, some downside risk could be hedged away and we could more reliably assess the probable outcomes through statistical and economic analysis. Such an approach is the driving force behind Vega’s stellar back test results. As it turns out, being humble pays dividends.\r\n\r\nIn the coming weeks, we’ll be releasing details of our 25 year back test which demonstrates Vega’s strong returns over many bull and bear markets.\r\n\r\n<!-- <fw_preview_session>1525350087701</fw_preview_session> -->', 'How Vega uses probability to outperform', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2146-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:27:50', '2018-08-23 11:27:50', '', 2146, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2146-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
