(2807, 1, '2018-08-23 11:29:10', '2018-08-23 11:29:10', 'Redeploying capital from the QQQ to SPY\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: SPYing an opportunity\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nReaders will recall that the Vega Fund recently (see <a href=\"http://vegacapital.net/2018/03/29/how-vega-minimises-downside-risk/\">here</a>) held a short position in some July 150 strike put options on the NASDAQ mini index (QQQ). At the time these options had an inflated premium of $6 (Vega entered at $6.30) as technology stocks came under pressure amid the Facebook inquiry, the crash of an autonomous car and concerns that governments would regulate companies such as Facebook and Google more stringently.\r\n\r\nOur philosophy at the Vega Fund is that these events are largely noise. Looking longer term, most firms (not all) which dominate market indices have strong competitive positions and a long run of profitability ahead of them whether regulated or not….One must remember that the Tobacco industry enjoyed many a profitable year post heavy regulation – a counter-intuitive fact!\r\n\r\nHowever a July 2018 put is not a long term bet - it’s clearly short term. The underlying stock index should behave largely randomly within this time-frame hence we employed statistics combined with Vega’s macroeconomic analysis to assess the opportunity and risk. The outcome of this was that the option which was yielding a 25 per cent return to July if priced fairly should have offered only 15 per cent or less (embedded alpha of 10 per cent). In addition, whilst a financial market shock was possible, it was also statically unlikely. Hence combined with some hedges against disaster and as one of many positions in the portfolio, Vega wrote the put.\r\n\r\nSaid put is now trading for around $3.20 and in our view isn’t such a compelling opportunity anymore. The potential returns have fallen considerably and the risks are changing. As options approach maturity, they become more sensitive to market shocks relative to that of options which have more time until expiration. The reason is that if there is a sudden drop in the market, the near term option may go in-the-money and not have ample time for the market price to correct before expiration.\r\n\r\nHowever new opportunities have arisen elsewhere – particularly in the SPY (S&amp;P500 SPDR mini) and we have redeployed capital accordingly.\r\n\r\nVega last week wrote a put option on March 2019 SPY 260 puts for $13.40 (last price was $13.90 so we’re down slightly). We received $1,340 per put and put up around $4,400 in margin per put. The return on capital employed at the time was around 30 per cent with embedded alpha of 5 per cent (at fair value, the option should have only been offering a 25 per cent return).\r\n\r\nOur outlook on the SPY is neutral to positive and this is required for a written put position to yield us a return. The economy in our view is strong (see <a href=\"http://vegacapital.net/2018/04/08/how-does-vega-see-the-us-economic-cycle/\">here</a>), price momentum has weakened (not conclusively) and volatility clustering post the February correction has abated. Now this opportunity is nowhere as good as the QQQ trade prior however with a 30 per cent potential return on capital employed it was a welcome addition to the portfolio.\r\n\r\nIt’s important we clarify however that this trade on the SPY has not been made in isolation, it\'s one part of a much larger portfolio and has been made in conjunction with various hedges. <strong>Hence we’re not advising clients or readers to make the same trade</strong>. As always, please seek the counsel of a licenced professional before making any investment decisions.', 'SPYing an opportunity', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2145-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:29:10', '2018-08-23 11:29:10', '', 2145, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2145-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2808, 1, '2018-08-23 11:30:31', '2018-08-23 11:30:31', 'Are we calling time for the US economy?\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: Vega holds 50 per cent cash….are we bearish?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nFor anyone looking who’s looked at the Vega portfolio of late (a very select few individuals at this point in time), they would rightly observe that the Fund is only 50 per cent invested with the remaining 50 per cent being held in cash. So does this mean we’ve become suddenly bearish on the US economy?\r\n\r\nIn short <strong>no</strong>. To answer this question, we must understand how Vega views cash as an investment. Cash as observed by Warren Buffet is one of the poorest investments available – it by default provides no real capital growth over time and hence to hold significant quantities of cash is an inefficient use of capital.\r\n\r\nTypically, many investors will hold a portion of their portfolio in cash – waiting for an opportunistic entry into an investment or because there doesn’t appear to be ample investment opportunities in the market. Yet Vega is not finding investment opportunities to be scarce – quite the contrary, there are many.\r\n\r\nVega is holding 50 per cent of its portfolio in cash for several reasons.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>The investments in the portfolio have already very high payoffs, so even with substantial levels of cash, the portfolio has been constructed with a high probability of out-performance. Hence the portfolio does not need to take on more risk than it already is.</li>\r\n 	<li>Vega will always hold ample reserves of cash in order to handle any short term events where volatility is elevated. It’s notable that due to the high volatility of the options market, new opportunities arise at a higher frequency than that of the stock market.</li>\r\n 	<li>There is the potential for even better opportunities to arise which require higher levels of margin capital – the Vega Fund is hence well positioned to take advantage of these events.</li>\r\n 	<li>There is little need to go over-weight on risk when the market is fairly mature and economic/geopolitical risks are rising.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nHence we have a solid case for holding significant quantities of cash. We may hold more or less in the future, but that depends on what opportunities are out there and economic risk levels.\r\n\r\nTo summarise, the implied return of Vega’s cash reserves is more than just interest earned, it\'s allows us to easily position into better opportunities and hold the portfolio through volatile periods. In addition, the Vega portfolio has ample exposure and embedded alpha sufficient to generate market beating levels of performance for our clients.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund will be open to sophisticated investors <strong>by invitation</strong> from the 1st of July 2018.\r\n\r\n<!-- <fw_preview_session>1523848878574</fw_preview_session> -->', 'Vega holds 50 per cent cash….are we bearish?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2144-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:30:31', '2018-08-23 11:30:31', '', 2144, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2144-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2809, 1, '2018-08-23 11:31:14', '2018-08-23 11:31:14', 'How does Vega see the US economic cycle?\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: How does Vega see the US economic cycle?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nA core piece of the Vega investment strategy is to manage client’s capital with respect to the phase of the current economic/business cycle. Now if this were a simple process then everyone would be doing it but since it’s quite complicated, we’re going to outlay a little of our thinking on the matter.\r\n\r\nCycles typically have four parts, an expansion, a peak, a recession and a recovery. To start we can make some fairly obvious observations about the US economy.\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>It doesn’t appear to be in recession.</li>\r\n 	<li>It has experienced a recovery post the contraction of 2009.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWhich leaves us to wonder whether the current economy is in an expansionary phase or has peaked. It would be difficult to determine the answer with 100 per cent certainty so we’ll speak in terms of probabilities.\r\n\r\nIf you’re a frequent reader of Howard Mark’s literature you’ll have read his January memo to clients (<a href=\"https://www.oaktreecapital.com/docs/default-source/memos/latest-thinking.pdf\">link</a>). Marks\' makes some pertinent economic observations:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><em>The U.S. economy is chugging along, and the recovery that started in 2009 has become one of the longest in history (103 months old at this point). The rest of the world’s economies are joining in for that rare thing, worldwide growth. Most economies seem to be gaining rather than losing steam, and they don’t appear likely to run out of it anytime soon.”</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>Since the economic recovery hasn’t been marked by excesses to the upside, when a recession eventually does occur, it doesn’t have to be extreme. In short, no boom, no bust.</em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>The unemployment rate is down to 4.1%, nearly the lowest level in 60 years, meaning we’re nearing “full employment” (albeit with an unusually low percentage of adults participating in the workforce). </em></li>\r\n 	<li><em>The low levels of inflation worldwide mean central bankers needn’t rush to raise interest rates to restrain it. There’s no obvious reason to predict hyperinflation. Thus the near-term rise in interest rates – while probable – can be expected to be gradual and limited in scope.</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSo in short the economy appears to be growing and economic indicators are positive. Given this as well as Vega’s algorithm based economic analysis, we would estimate that the likelihood that US is still expanding is perhaps 60/70% and the likelihood of a peak 30/40% - perhaps the latter more recently elevated by the possibility of a trade war between the US and China - but let’s not get carried away.\r\n\r\nThe latest economic data point for the US economy has been non-farm payrolls and the unemployment rate which came out Friday at 4.1% (consensus expectations was 4.0%). Since the economy is close to full employment, the natural process would be for wages from here to increase and lead to later inflation and some tempering via interest rates, but this is a gradual process as Marks noted.\r\n\r\nSo how is Vega’s option portfolio positioned for this environment given this view? Like Marks, we’re cautiously optimistic. The Vega portfolio is tilted towards expecting an inflation in stock market prices over the medium term. Economic risk however is increasing.\r\n\r\nOur hedging book is well placed to withstand any unforeseeable market volatility and we’re pleased with the margin of safety between market prices and the valuation of our portfolio. Given another quote from the memo, this seems prudent.\r\n\r\n<em>“Most valuation parameters are either the richest ever (Buffett ratio of stock market capitalization to GDP, price-to-sales ratio, the VIX, bond yields, private equity transaction multiples, real estate capitalisation ratios) or among the highest in history (p/e ratios, Shiller cycle-adjusted p/e ratio).”</em><!-- <fw_preview_session>1523192429084</fw_preview_session> -->', 'How does Vega see the US economic cycle?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2143-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:31:14', '2018-08-23 11:31:14', '', 2143, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/2143-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
