(2811, 1, '2018-08-23 11:32:19', '2018-08-23 11:32:19', 'How does the Vega fund minimise downside risk?\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nMemo to: Vega Capital clients\r\nFrom: Scott Shuttleworth\r\nSubject: How the Vega fund minimises downside risk\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<em>Neither the information, nor any opinion, contained on this Website  </em><em>constitutes a solicitation or offer by Vega Capital Pty Ltd (“Vega </em><em>Capital”) or its affiliates to buy or sell any securities, futures, options or other financial instruments. Decisions based on information contained on </em><em>this Website are the sole responsibility of the visitor whom we would </em><em>encourage to seek relevant advice from a licenced professional.</em>\r\n\r\nThere\'s no escaping that if you sell a put option, you are taking on a small but very real risk that you could owe the buyer of said option a lot of money in the future. This is actually a necessity. To illustrate, let\'s consider the following example.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund recently wrote an option on the QQQ (NASDAQ mini index) for $600 per contract that has 113 days to expiry with a strike of 150. The QQQ at the time was trading at about 157 so we have somewhat of a buffer before the strike. We\'re required to put up about $2400 in margin so our return is 25% for 113 days. By inspection, we can see that before we begin to take a loss, the QQQ would need to fall from 157 to below 144 (9%) by July which is not impossible but is statistically unlikely. Since the probability of a loss is unlikely, the probability of profit by reflection is likely.\r\n\r\nI\'m sure you can see where I\'m going with this - for a likely as well as high return over such a short period, the writer of this contract must be willing to accept a large loss if the QQQ falls a lot. Otherwise, there\'s nothing in it for the buyer of the contract and the trade won\'t occur. As custodians of our clients capital, this presents downside risk which we must manage.\r\n\r\nWe first note that whilst the option will pay us a 25% return, Vega\'s proprietary model tells us that the \'fair\' return should only be 15% (a margin of safety of 10%). This means that option buyers are craving security so much that they\'re willing to pay over the fair price for it - a happy coincidence as we\'re willing to sell overpriced options. Hence the contract isn\'t really fair - we have a mathematical edge from the start. This doesn\'t mean that we can\'t take a loss on this particular trade (it\'s just that we have a bigger buffer for losses than we theoretically should have).\r\n\r\nVega\'s algorithm will only ever enter into mis-priced securities which adds to both downside protection and investor returns over time.\r\n\r\nWe can further reduce the potential for a large loss by only selling option premium in less risky economic times whilst moving to cash or buying protection during risky times. As many of those reading will know, The Vega Fund has a set of algorithms which determine how risky the economy and financial markets are. Currently the algorithms are telling us that the risk of a big loss is low (but such a view is subject to continuous monitoring so please, don\'t take this as a recommendation). In doing this, we further skew the odds and returns in favour of our investors.\r\n\r\nFinally, in conjunction to Vega\'s portfolio, we run a separate portfolio which hedges against sudden unforeseeable market drops - especially useful for this particular investment.\r\n\r\nTo summarise, due to lucrative option premiums and a strong economic environment Vega is currently writing options over many broad based market indices but is then also taking on risk which must be managed. Vega manages portfolio risk against the broader economic/financial environment, hedging excess risk and only entering into contracts with a good margin of safety.\r\n\r\nThe Vega fund will be open to sophisticated investors <strong>by invitation</strong> from the 1st of July 2018.', 'How Vega minimises downside risk', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1205-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-08-23 11:32:19', '2018-08-23 11:32:19', '', 1205, 'http://vegacapital.net/new/uncategorized/1205-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
